This is the current method signature:

``` java
public Class<Serializable> getFetchRestrictionRoot(AdminUser currentUser, Class<Serializable> ceilingEntity, List<FilterMapping> filterMappings)
```

The intention is so that you can do things like:

``` java
public Class<Serializable> getFetchRestrictionRoot(AdminUser currentUser, Class<Serializable> ceilingEntity, List<FilterMapping> filterMappings) {
    return MyProduct.class;
}
```

But the interface contract is too specific; that will return an error.

The method signature needs to change to instead have this:

``` java
public Class<? extends Serializable> getFetchRestrictionRoot(AdminUser currentUser, Class<Serializable> ceilingEntity, List<FilterMapping> filterMappings)
```

looking at the `markPaymentAsInvalid` method in `org.broadleafcommerce.core.payment.service.DefaultPaymentGatewayCheckoutService` - the intention is to set the payments and all of its child transactions to `Archived` as specified in this issue: https://github.com/BroadleafCommerce/BroadleafCommerce/issues/1160 --- 

However, there does not seem to be a wrapping transaction, so not sure how this change is actually persisted. An example scenario may be when you get an unsuccessful response back from the gateway.

This change seems to be in 3.1.9-GA+

```
    @Override
    public void markPaymentAsInvalid(Long orderPaymentId) {
        OrderPayment payment = orderPaymentService.readPaymentById(orderPaymentId);
        if (payment == null) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Could not find payment with id " + orderPaymentId);
        }
        // Do not do an actual delete here, otherwise Hibernate will screw up the relationships by setting parent transactions
        // to null because of the cascades. This manifests itself when you have an AUTHORIZE_AND_CAPTURE transaction and
        // then an immediate VOID (like if there is an exception in the checkout workflow). The VOID transaction should
        // have its parent set to the AUTHORIZE_AND_CAPTURE transaction which works up until we call Hibernate's delete
        // on the payment. By cascading down to the transaction, Hibernate goes and removes the parentTransaction relationship
        // from the VOID transaction
        // The fix is to set archived statuses manually and not rely on Hibernate's @SqlDelete
        payment.setArchived('Y');
        for (PaymentTransaction transaction : payment.getTransactions()) {
            transaction.setArchived('Y');
        }
    }
```

One solution is to explicitly save the payment after setting the flag. Like so:

```
        payment.setArchived('Y');
        for (PaymentTransaction transaction : payment.getTransactions()) {
            transaction.setArchived('Y');
        }
        orderPaymentService.save(payment);
```

