Somewhat related to #1348.

Let's say we have this example:

```
public class MySku extends SkuImpl
    @Column("NEW_PROPERTY")
     public String myProperty;
     ...

    public String getMyProperty() {
        return myProperty;
    }
}
```

Then ensure that you create a `MySku` instance in the database and then add that to your cart. In order to get around the problem of a ton of joins with catalog and order extensions (see #1209), we have changed the relationship from `DiscreteOrderItem` to `Sku` to be `FetchType.LAZY`:

```
@ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY, targetEntity = SkuImpl.class, optional=false)
@JoinColumn(name = "SKU_ID", nullable = false)
@Index(name="DISCRETE_SKU_INDEX", columnNames={"SKU_ID"})
@AdminPresentation(friendlyName = "DiscreteOrderItemImpl_Sku", order=Presentation.FieldOrder.SKU,
        group = OrderItemImpl.Presentation.Group.Name.Catalog, groupOrder = OrderItemImpl.Presentation.Group.Order.Catalog)
@AdminPresentationToOneLookup()
protected Sku sku;
```

So, when you call `discreteOrderItem.getSku()`, the instance that you actually get back is a javaassist object (aka a Hibernate proxy) that conforms to SkuImpl (it just looks at the `@ManyToOne` information to determine this). Thus, this invocation will fail with a class cast exception:

```
// Throws ClassCastException
String myProperty = ((MySku) discreteOrderItem.getSku()).getMyProperty();
```

Casting the `getSku()` call to a `Sku` or `SkuImpl` will always succeed.

Here's where it gets fun. Because it's loaded lazily, when you try to actually get a property from the Sku it goes and looks it up (db or cache) and then gives you the right type. Thus, if you do this then it will succeed:

```
// force a load of the Sku
discreteOrderItem.getSku().getId();
String myProperty = ((MySku) discreteOrderItem.getSku()).getMyProperty();
// all good
```

The above is a workaround. What we should do in the framework is in the getter, go ahead and refresh the Sku instance. According to the almighty internet at http://stackoverflow.com/questions/17155452/hibernate-lazy-loading-for-reverse-one-to-one-workaround-how-does-this-work, it looks like the addition of `@LazyToOne(LazyToOneOption.NO_PROXY)` to that property should work because then whenever the reference is accessed the instance will be refreshed automatically.

The DiscreteOrderItem -> Sku relationship is 1 instance but I'm sure there are others. Doing a quick search in my projects:
